Carson, strong proposal. Option A is the right call. Here's my CSS/frontend feedback:

## CSS `:has()` Progressive Disclosure -- Full Support

This is exactly the kind of modern CSS feature we should be using. `:has()` is supported in all our target browsers (last 2 versions of Chrome, Firefox, Safari, Edge -- Firefox added support in 121, Dec 2023). The disclosure pattern is clean:

```css
/* Project fields hidden by default */
.inbox-item__project-fields {
    display: none;
}

/* Revealed when Project radio is checked */
.inbox-item__clarify:has(input[value="project"]:checked) .inbox-item__project-fields {
    display: flex;
    gap: var(--space-xs);
}
```

This works without JS, degrades gracefully (if `:has()` somehow isn't supported, the project fields are hidden and users fall back to the Next Action path), and follows our progressive enhancement principle.

## HTML Structure Feedback

Your proposed structure is solid. A few CSS-relevant refinements:

1. **Radio group styling**: The radios should use a horizontal flex layout with pill-like styling to feel like a toggle, not a traditional form radio group. This keeps the "sorting mail" feel compact:

```css
.inbox-item__clarify-options {
    display: flex;
    gap: var(--space-xs);
}

.inbox-item__clarify-options label {
    display: inline-flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: var(--space-xs);
    font-size: var(--font-size-sm);
    padding: var(--space-xs) var(--space-sm);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: var(--radius-full);
    cursor: pointer;
    color: var(--color-fg-muted);
}

/* Checked state -- matches our filter pill pattern */
.inbox-item__clarify-options label:has(input:checked) {
    color: white;
    background-color: var(--color-primary);
    border-color: var(--color-primary);
}

/* Hide the native radio visually but keep it accessible */
.inbox-item__clarify-options input[type="radio"] {
    position: absolute;
    opacity: 0;
    pointer-events: none;
}
```

This reuses the visual language of the filter pills from the Next Actions page -- consistent and familiar.

2. **The Trash option**: Should Trash be a radio option in the same group, or stay as a separate button? I'd argue it stays separate -- trashing is destructive and should be visually distinct (muted text button, not a radio pill). Mixing it into the radio group would give it equal visual weight with constructive paths.

3. **`flex-wrap: wrap` on the clarify form**: The inbox item already has `flex-wrap: wrap`. The clarify form inside should also wrap so on narrow viewports, the radio options, context select, project fields, and submit button can stack naturally.

4. **Focus management**: When the user selects the "Project" radio, the newly revealed "First action" input should receive focus. This can be done with a small CSS-only approach (`:has()` + `autofocus` won't work since the element is already in the DOM), so we'd need a tiny JS enhancement:

```js
// Progressive enhancement: focus first-action input when Project is selected
document.body.addEventListener('change', function(e) {
    if (e.target.name === 'clarify_type' && e.target.value === 'project') {
        var fields = e.target.closest('.inbox-item__clarify');
        var input = fields && fields.querySelector('.inbox-item__project-fields input');
        if (input) input.focus();
    }
});
```

This is non-critical (the form works without it), but improves the flow.

## Token References for New Styles

- Radio pills: `--space-xs`, `--space-sm`, `--color-border`, `--radius-full`, `--color-primary`, `--font-size-sm`
- Project fields container: `--space-xs` gap, `--space-sm` padding
- First action input: inherits base layer input styles, just needs `min-inline-size: 8rem` and `flex: 1`
- Transition on radio pills: `@media (prefers-reduced-motion: no-preference)` with `--transition-fast`

## Summary

Option A with `:has()` is the right approach. The CSS is straightforward, follows our established patterns (filter pills, flex layouts, logical properties), and provides genuine progressive enhancement. Ready to review once you start coding.

